A Virtual Conversation with Dr. Stanley Andrisse Wednesday, January 19, 2021 6:00 pm In his new book, From Prison Cells to PhD: It is Never Too Late to Do Good, Dr. Andrisse tells the story of his journey from incarcerated person to PhD student, endocrinologist, diabetes researcher at Johns Hopkins University, nonprofit director, and advocate. His book illustrates the obstacles imposed by the criminal justice system on rehabilitation, receiving second chances, and realizing one‚Äôs potential. In hosting this event, The Alliance hopes to inspire attendees to advocate for the dismantling of structural barriers imposed on incarcerated people and support ongoing anti-racist work in our community. https://cca.wildapricot.org/event-4586642...:=:https://cca.wildapricot.org/Sys/Error/404 This event is free. #BlackHistoryMonth Spotlight: Negro Ensemble Company Playwright Douglas Turner Ward and producer-actor Robert Hooks dreamed of creating a theater company run by and for the Black community. A chance viewing from a NY theater critic of the pair's urban youth acting program became the spark they needed to make their dream a reality. The duo joined forces with theater manager Gerald S. Krone and got to work. They soon found a home at the St. Marks Playhouse in New York, and with the help of a donation from the Ford Foundation, the Negro Ensemble Company was officially born in 1967. Despite numerous ups and downs and financial issues, NEC has solidified its place as one of the most influential Black theater companies of all time. They have produced over 200 plays, won numerous awards from Tonys to the Pulitzer Prize, and have given a platform to some of the greatest Black voices of all time including, Debbie Allen, Hinton, Battle, Angela Bassett, Laurence Fishburne, Danny Glover, Samuel L. Jackson, Ruben Santiago-Hudson, Denzel Washington, and countless others. üì∑: From left, Adolph Caesar, Denzel Washington and Peter Friedman in the 1981 Negro Ensemble Company production of ‚ÄúA Soldier‚Äôs Play (Credit: Bert Andrews)

On this day in history--6/19/1865--the Union Army arrives in Galveston, TX under the leadership of General Gordon Granger, who announces to the people of Texas that all enslaved African Americans are free. Learn more here from the Smithsonian: https://nmaahc.si.edu/explore/stories/what-juneteenth #juneteenth

What is Juneteenth? Lincoln proclaimed slaves free in 1863, but it wasn‚Äôt until 6/19/1865 that it was enforced by the Union in states such as Texas when the news (& Union soldiers) finally reached slaves in Galveston. Read more info from the Smithsonian: https://nmaahc.si.edu/explore/stories/what-juneteenth

AVAILABLE- SUPER NICE HORSE! ü¶Ñ This mare just passed ALL her assessments in ONE DAY. Misspotogold is a 2017 mare who stands at approximately 16 hands (and growing a bit). This mare is a wonderful horse to be around and work with. This horse is quiet, mannerly, a decent keeper, barefoot, has no vices and will stand tied or cross tied. Misspotogold tacks up easily, has started learning how to lunge, likes working on the ground and is attentive to her handlers and rider. This mare stood quietly to be tacked up as well as at the mounting block. PERFECT HOME - Adult ammy who is seeking loving mare friend who wants to please, trail ride and conquer some pleasure riding with some weekend outings here and there. The video link below (warning, about 8 minutes long) shows how we really take our time with our horses to offer enough time to comfortably and confidently start back under saddle. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KELCz6WQnug Many of you see horses in our program for MONTHS- or even a year or so. There's a reason for that- this video is proof enough. After passing her leading, grooming and crosstie assessments, Misspotogold tacked easily and gave a lovely walk, trot and canter on a loose rein. We feel that a rubber mullen mouth (non jointed rubber coated) would be her perfect bit as she does not pull. Her rider described her as a soft ride requiring lots of leg. Her rider also noted that she was very kind and willing to move off leg. You will see mid-video how we teach obstacles and desensitize the horses in our program. As Misspotogold rehabiliated an injury successfully, she was offered AMPLE downtime after exiting rehabilitation free in the herd to graze and relax. Missppotogold crossed logs, cantered with the flag and navigated ground poles and a small jump. She then was able to work in the arena and then headed out on the trail by herself (again, her FIRST ride off the track) and walked around the trails quietly alone. This was this horse's first ride (today). We feel she would be an EXCELLENT trail/pleasure horse for someone. Serious adopters only. What if "A Grunt's Life" was real? What would the news coming out of Afghanistan look like? MUSA QALA - A Taliban detachment of videographers assigned to film an attack on US forces accidentally identified a weakness in their force: Taliban are poor judges of cover vs. concealment. The revelation came to Taliban leadership after reviewing the footage and seeing their fighters taking cover behind empty, plastic 55gal drums, hay piles, and other objects that only protect against sight and sound, but not small arms fire. "Many of these men have only fought in mountains," said Abdul Yasir, Commander of Taliban forces in the Helmand Province. "There it is all-mountain, and tree, and rock. Very good covers. Less to think about." According to Yasir, the problem begins when his men come down from the mountains to fight in villages and have to choose between man-made options for cover. "Is not really a problem," Yasir continued, "I don't actually expect my men to win fights. Real win comes from chipping away at America's resolve until they pack up and leave. Should be any year now." üá∫üá∏ Hollywood makes TV for civilians. We‚Äôre veterans making TV for Veterans https://veterantv.app.link/a-grunt-s-life

#bellhooks was many things, but at her core, she was always an educator challenging us to learn, grow, and seek resolutions through our challenges. ‚ÄúFor me, forgiveness and compassion are always linked: how do we hold people accountable for wrongdoing and yet at the same time remain in touch with their humanity enough to believe in their capacity to be transformed?‚Äù #EmpoweredWomenEmpowerWomen #BlackHistoryMonth #BHM2022 #BlackFeminist

During #BlackHerstoryMonth, we would be remiss if we didn‚Äôt acknowledge the contributions and legacy of Bell Hooks. When speaking on feminism bell hooks once said, ‚ÄúSexism has never rendered women powerless. It has either suppressed their strength or exploited it.‚Äù It is because of the vision and tireless work of #Blackfeminists like Bell Hooks, that we are reminded that even in our oppression, the experiences and wisdom of Black women continues to lead the way to liberation for all women. We thank her for providing us new perspectives which empower women and the tools to be more inclusive in our feminist movements. #EmpoweredWomenEmpowerWomen

Through books like ‚ÄúSister Outsider: Essays and Speeches,‚Äù ‚ÄúThe Transformation of Silence into Language & Action,‚Äù and ‚ÄúBlack Women Writers at Work,‚Äù Audre Lorde curated a mighty voice for herself and paved the way for countless Black women who followed to be open with their experiences and use their life experience as a tool for liberation. ‚ÄúI write for those women who do not speak, for those who do not have a voice because they were so terrified, because we are taught to respect fear more than ourselves. We‚Äôve been taught that silence would save us, but it won‚Äôt,‚Äù Lorde once said. During #BlackHerstoryMonth, we celebrate Audre Lorde and all the space she made for black women -- particularly those in the margins and intersections -- to leave fear and silence behind and build the courage to lead the feminist movements of the future!

Conversations around motherhood are often framed by the language of individual choice, but the current disparities in breastfeeding rates and maternal mortality between Black women and white women in this country can‚Äôt be attributed to individual choices. They‚Äôre a result of centuries of racist practices, policies, and beliefs that continue to impact Black and brown mothers. Bringing equity to healthcare starts with a hard look at American history. For a more comprehensive look at the history of maternal health inequities in America, and for the links to the sources, head to the link in our bio. Shout out to @theirthapp, @everymomcounts, @support_rose and @blackmamasmatter for their important advocacy work to address ongoing maternal health inequities.

Please join us virtually for tgiFHI THIS Fri. 2/11 from 9:30 - 11:00 a.m. EST. Kevin Richardson, Assistant Professor of Philosophy at Duke, will be giving a talk entitled ‚ÄúAre Black Men a Counterexample to Feminism?‚Äù Professor Richardson‚Äôs research focuses on two broad questions: How are social kinds (like gender and race) constructed by social groups? And how do linguistic practices (like assertions about racial identity) shape social reality? In this talk, he will draw on the thesis of Tommy Curry‚Äôs book The Man-Not, which claims that Black men are oppressed in virtue of being men, and examine how it contradicts ‚Äúclassic feminist theory, which holds that no man, of any race, can be oppressed in virtue of being a man.‚Äù Disagreeing with Curry‚Äôs view that Black men are oppressed on the basis of their gender, Prof. Richardson argues that we can better understand the plight of Black men if we have a more sophisticated framework for analyzing oppression. What that framework entails will be laid out in the talk. Don‚Äôt miss it! To register, please go to: http://duke.is/cq26e:=:https://duke.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_f3haLOTlRHS2e6OwmyB6gg Cosponsors of this event include Gender, Sexuality, and Feminist Studies at Duke University; Duke Philosophy; Duke University Department of Religious Studies

‚ÄúMy call to the world, especially people with special needs, is to resist and never give up under any circumstances.‚Äù Meet Rozhin. Born with disabilities, Rozhin relied on her family to help with routine tasks. Due to the ongoing war in #Syria, her family was forced to migrate to Iraq. When her mother passed away, Rozhin was stuck living with her father‚Äôs new wife and children, who provided little-to-no support. She felt completely isolated. Thankfully, Rozhin began attending a UNFPA safe space to learn skills to take care of herself and gained income-generating skills, resilience and confidence, and friendships. ‚ÄúMy disability is not a burden,‚Äù said Rozhin. ‚ÄúIn fact, it is a source of strength.‚Äù Learn more about Rozhin and other women who received care from UNFPA: https://buff.ly/3qXZ3eV:=:https://www.friendsofunfpa.org/another-year-of-war-stories-from-the-syrian-diaspora/

The YWCA of Northwest Ohio has announced the national launch of the Stand Against Racism Challenge: A Virtual Community of Growth. Previously known as the 21-Day Racial Equity and Social Justice Challenge, this is the same program developed by YWCA Greater Cleveland and brought to our community by the YWCA of Northwest Ohio with all new content and challenge material for 2022. They're also offering new ways to get involved and stay engaged! The Stand Against Racism Challenge is an exciting and free opportunity for organizations, groups, and individuals to dive deep into racial equity and social justice. Participants will receive a daily email and will be able to download an app for their phone or visit the challenge website to engage with curated articles, podcasts, videos, activities, and more. The SAR Challenge registration went live on February 7th, and the challenge will begin April 4th and continue (Monday ‚Äì Friday) through May 2nd. Due to the high demand, space is limited so please sign up today!

As our Black History Month celebrations continue, we would like to share a story from one of our own - Jelita Bridgeforth, HR director - and her family, Bridgeforth Farms. Founded in 1877, in Tanner, Alabama, George Bridgeforth, Sr., a former slave, began purchasing land after the civil war, his ambition was to start a family & grow his farm. Today, it's a 4th & 5th generation black-owned family farm that expands over 10,000 acres, producing cotton, corn, soybeans, & wheat, along with a 5,000-acre fruit orchard. "legacy, entrepreneurship, pride, success, & strength." is what the cotton from these lands represent to her & her family, says Jelita. Look for Bridgeforth Farms tags as part of Target's Black History Collection; living examples of their ancestor's dreams & hard work. Learn more about Bridgeforth Farms here http://ow.ly/T8RR50HR5gL:=:https://www.becauseofthemwecan.com/blogs/news/black-owned-cotton-farm-becomes-supplier-for-target-s-black-history-month-t-shirts #livingthedream
